    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-03-27T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-03-27T17:00:00-05:00" n="206"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d206">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.115/594: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-03-27T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 27, 1939—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>74. Reference Tientsin’s 44, March 25, 11 a.m.<note n="52" xml:id="d206fn52">
                        <ref target="frus1939v03#pg_387">Vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, p.
                            387</ref>.</note> Peiping’s 148, March 24, 4 p.m., transmitting your
                    143, March 23, 9 p.m., and previous telegrams in regard to the search of
                    foreigners at Tientsin.</p>
                <pb facs="0176" n="170" xml:id="pg_170"/>
                <p>Although this Government does not admit the right of Japanese authorities acting
                    directly or indirectly to search American nationals residing in China, the
                    Department is of the opinion that the situation at Tientsin does not, in view of
                    the information contained in Tientsin’s telegram no. 44, warrant the making of
                    representations at Tokyo. However, the Department desires that the Consulate
                    General at Tientsin watch the situation carefully and report developments
                    promptly in order that appropriate action may be taken should the circumstances
                    warrant.</p>
                <p>The Department has replied to an <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> of March 23,
                    1939, from the British Embassy<note n="53" xml:id="d206fn53">
                        <hi rend="italic">Aide-mémoire</hi> and reply not printed.</note> in regard
                    to the matter under reference along the lines of the foregoing paragraph.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Chungking and Tientsin.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
